A lot of human culture really is accumulated experience transmission:

* stories,
* laws,
* rituals,
* memes,
* advice,
* warnings,
* myths,
* philosophies,
* and institutions
    are all ways humans compress and pass forward lived or interpreted experience.

And yes, sometimes people exaggerate, posture, mythologize, or pretend to wisdom they didn’t truly earn. Humans curate narratives about themselves constantly:

* to gain status,
* protect identity,
* inspire others,
* sell ideas,
* or hide insecurity.

But not all transmitted experience is fake just because some is performative. Even imperfect stories can still carry useful patterns:

* cautionary lessons,
* emotional truths,
* coordination mechanisms,
* or distilled heuristics.

The difficult skill is discernment:

* separating signal from theater,
* wisdom from branding,
* experience from imitation,
* and principles from performance.

That’s part of why direct experience changes people so much. Some things can be explained symbolically, but not fully understood until lived.